Triumph of right-wing populists in Austria, totalling 29 percent
After the first preliminary results, the early parliamentary elections on Sunday in Austria brought a noticeable weakening of both parties of the previous grand coalition and a significant strengthening of the right-wing populist parties.
The Austrian People ’ s Party (ÖVP) suffered particularly severe losses, where the position of the previous chairman, Wilhelm Molterer, is seriously at risk.
In contrast, the leader of the Coalition for the Future of Austria (BZÖ), Carinthian Governor Jörg Haider, is preparing for a triumphant return to federal politics.
According to the results so far, the Social Democracy (SPÖ) remains the strongest force in the country with 29.8 percent of the votes, but compared to the last elections in 2006 it loses 5.5 percent of the votes.
The ÖVP scored even worse, losing almost nine percent of the votes at 25.6 percent.
These are the worst results of these two major parties in the post-war history of Austria, and particularly of the People's Party, which called for early elections, this is a truly catastrophic result.
At the beginning of July, when the ÖVP had left the coalition, the People ’ s Party still had a clear lead over the SPÖ.
But voters probably punished the party for failing to govern.
Already in the first reactions to the results there were speculations about a possible resignation of the party chairman and former Vice-Chancellor Wilhelm Molterer.
Observers believe that this could be the case as early as Monday at an extraordinary meeting of the party ’ s executive board.
Such a development would probably pave the way to the most likely way out of the electoral debacle, i.e. to a renewal of the grand coalition of SPÖ and ÖVP.
In view of the strengthening of both right-wing populist parties - the Freedom Party (FPÖ) received 18 percent of the votes for the time being, and the BZÖ eleven percent - the Social Democrats simultaneously expressed their fear that the year 1999 could be repeated when the People's Party had reached agreements with the populists (at that time the FPÖ was still united, in 2005 it split from the BZÖ) regarding a common government, which had even caused sanctions on the part of the European Union.
Jörg Haider, who has already stated that he is prepared to cooperate with any party, is obviously counting on this development and assumes a return to Vienna in Austrian federal politics.
The Green Party also entered parliament, but suffered slight losses and dropped from third to fifth place among Austrian political parties.
No other party has probably mastered the four per cent barrier and has therefore not entered parliament.
