A seabed larger than the mainland
The coastal states today vehemently declared their entitlement to the new maritime areas.
According to a UN convention, they make use of their rights, which they agreed on in Montego Bay, Jamaica, in 1982.
It is mainly the area of the so-called continental shelf, which often extends up to a few hundred kilometres from the shore of a country into the sea.
According to the Convention, this country has an exclusive right to all sources of continental shelf.
"Simply put, the continental shelf is the part of the seabed and its soles that is a natural continuation of the continent below the sea surface.
It crosses the boundaries of the sea, often the boundary of two hundred nautical miles of the so-called exclusive economic zone, "Mikulka explains.
The application submitted by the country concerned to the Commission for the establishment of the external borders of the continental shelf must be substantiated by extensive scientific and technical documentation, based on many costly studies and measurements.
It is the result of many years of preparatory work.
"One of our tasks is to provide the Commission with legal and technical support.
The Commission has so far negotiated five applications from Russia, Brazil, Australia, Ireland and New Zealand.
Until now, only the last three countries have been successful, "adds Mikulka.
The success of Australia, which was the first country to be able to significantly enlarge its maritime areas, recently met with an international response.
But New Zealand is also a winner - the seabed expansion granted by the Commission last week is about 1.6 million square kilometres, about six times the size of the state itself.
Both countries have invested millions of dollars in the investigations.
The profits that will flow to them in the future from the use of the seabed will, as they promise, be invaluable.
Other states will also gradually submit their applications.
They can do so for ten years from the moment they ratify the 'Montego Bay Agreement'.
Where the continental shelf ends, begins the area of the ocean floor, which is referred to by the Convention as the "common heritage of mankind".
No state has a special status here.
The right to promote in this area is granted by an international institution established by the Convention.
"The seabed is not a gold-digger's land," says director Mikulka with a little exaggeration, adding that "its individual areas are clearly defined in law and the system is contractually anchored."
Czechs in the Pacific
