Organizers register rising reservation numbers
It seems to be a good winter for the German tour operators:
According to a study, the turnover of travel bookings for the coming months has increased significantly compared to the previous year - for the winter season even by more than 30 percent.
Despite weak economic prospects, a study shows that Germans ’ appetite for travel remains undimmed.
As reported by the German Travel Association (DRV) on Monday in Berlin, the travel agencies recorded an increase in turnover of 31 percent compared to the same period of the previous year.
According to an investigation by the market research institute GfK, bookings for the autumn months have already risen.
Thus the turnover plus of the travel agencies for October amounted to approximately eleven per cent in the comparison to 2007, communicated the DRV.
These results are based on figures from GfK, which evaluates the monthly booking data of 1200 German travel agencies and extrapolates them for the overall market.
This includes travel bookings made by the end of August 2008.
Due to the weak dollar exchange rate, trips to the USA are particularly in demand, said the DRV.
Here the booking increase would amount to approximately a third.
In addition, Spain, Turkey and Greece as well as the domestic regions are particularly sought after by the Germans.
Package travel is particularly popular, DRV President Klaus Laepple said.
In view of increasing costs for energy and food, the costs are "easier for customers to calculate than for individually organised holidays".
Consumers could save money through early bird discounts or all-inclusive offers, Laepple explained.
The summer months were also very well booked, so that compared to the previous year there would again be an increase in turnover - although according to a further study the number of Germans who undertook a trip decreased compared to the previous year.
