Turkey broadens diplomatic horizons
Long before Turkey aspired to join the European Union, European powers were interested in penetrating deep into Turkey ’ s hinterland.
On the eastern side of the Bosporus, perhaps just 20 steps within Asia, stands one of the finest relics of this failed imperial endeavor.
The Hydarpasha station was designed by the two German architects Otto Ritter and Helmut Conu in Neo-Renaissance style.
At least that is what the guides tell you.
The building sits astride the platforms with a tower at each corner of the front, looking like some provincial German town hall.
The rock is dirty.
The whole building decays about
But once inside the curved ticket office, there is no doubt about the grandeur of the project whose westernmost access was this.
The station was inaugurated in August 1908 by a German consortium, the Anatolia-Baghdad Society.
Germany, which was a late bloc in the imperialist game, had before its ambitions to dominate the Middle East by train to Damascus, Baghdad, and beyond to what is Saudi Arabia today.
But Germany ’ s imperialist ambitions faltered during World War I.
Its railway tracks were attacked by Lawrence of Arabia and his Arabs.
The relative isolation from its surrounding region, generated by the insurmountable boundaries of the Cold War, has disappeared.
British forces pulled out of Egypt and pushed the Turks and their German allies out of Palestine and Syria
And there was also bad news for Hyderpasha station.
In the year 1917 an ammunition train flew into the air, whereby the artful roof was destroyed.
Turkish sources say it was sabotage.
Since then it has slowly disintegrated, largely ignored by history.
Today, however, this railway line serves, at least symbolically, as a gateway to Anatolia and all east of it, to highlight the expansion of Turkey ’ s diplomatic horizon.
The ruling Justice and Development Party, the AKP, has introduced a completely new foreign policy for the country.
The relative isolation from neighboring regions generated by the Cold War borders has disappeared.
There is now a policy of rapprochement.
Remarkably, the Turkish Government has good relations with Israel and Syria, with the Palestinian factions Hamas and Fatah, with Iran and Iraq and, of course, with the European Union and the United States.
To assess the fundamentals of this new foreign policy, I boarded the night train to the Turkish capital, Ankara, to visit one of the AKP ’ s leading foreign policy experts, Turkish MP Suat Kiniklioglu.
The next morning, about ten and a half hours later, after a bumpy ride on tracks that produced the equal-step of the old world in the well-known documentary "The Night Mail", I arrived in the Turkish capital, which is regarded as a new city for the new secular state project of turning my back on the Ottoman past.
But the AKP, known for its Islamist roots, represents a paradigm shift in Turkish unity
This has caused some mistrust in the West, particularly in Washington.
A taxi took me to the AKP headquarters, a purpose-built, ultra-modern stone and steel structure, in a developing suburb, surrounded by semi-finished malls and pubs where middle managers in suits, both men and women, met to complete the first business of the day.
Suat Kiniklioglu could be a centre-right politician from almost every other European political party.
Suit, tie, I'm sure he even packed a Blackberry.
"The aim of the party's foreign policy is now to reintegrate Turkey with its immediate neighbours.
The Cold War was an exception, "he told me.
Turkey had been cut off from its hinterland.
Nowadays it has to look east and west at the same time.
There would not be either one or the other.
It would have to do both.
"But surely Turkey could at some point," I asked, "be forced to make up its mind?"
"Turkey," he said, "did not want to face this decision."
He then highlighted a point that almost everyone I spoke to here spoke to almost routinely: Turkey's relations, not only with the Middle East, but also with the Caucasus and around the Black Sea, are as beneficial to Europe and the United States as they are to Turkey.
With Turkey on board, the message seems to be that, figuratively speaking, Europe as a whole can travel east on those very railway tracks towards Asia and the Middle East.
Back at the Hydarpashas station, after another sleepless night, I thought of these two German rulers Mr. Ritter and Mr. Conu, who had watched the construction of this building 100 years ago.
How surprised they would have been to learn that Europe ’ s ambitions in the Middle East are now, to a large extent, in Turkey ’ s hands.
And as I waited at the pier for the ferry to take me back across the Bosphorus, I remembered that Turkey was always called 'the sick man of Europe' in those days.
At that time, at least, there did not seem to be much doubt as to which continent should be entitled to this fascinating country.
In memory of Vernon Handley and William Woodruff.
Mark Brown writes: As Guildford's musical director since 1962, Vernon "Death" Handley (obituary September 11) was responsible for the Guildford Philharmonic and Choir.
As part of his music program for the city, he founded his great youth choir, Proteus, the following year.
It was intended for young people up to 21 years of age, but when the choir sang for the last time in 1979, some of us were already in their late twenties - we simply refused to leave the choir.
The name "Proteus" (the mythological form changer) stood for the readiness and ability of the choir to tackle every piece of music that was presented to it, whether it was a madrigal or from the Messiah, whether a capella or with a full orchestra.
The musical versatility of such a young choir was often amazing, always exciting and persisted only thanks to the inspiration of that man and his enthusiasm for music, which continued for years.
How often did Tod urge us to "let the music speak for itself".
He used to say: "The composer knows what he wants."
It's all in music.
So it sings! "
His way of conducting was absolutely clear and precise, never overbearing but never exuberant.
No matter how high the musical level, he always demanded an even higher one.
John Frayn Turner writes:
If any conductor should have been knighted, it was Vernon Handley.
I knew him well during the last two decades, from 1962 to 1982, when he conducted the Guildford Philharmonic.
Over the last 40 years or so, I have written reviews for over a hundred of his concerts, and I can honestly say that I have never been disappointed by a single one - often inspired by them.
Death Handley was that rare combination of greatness and personal modesty.
He loathed conductors who, according to his words, simply "went peddling one or two well-known show horses in the world."
So many of us will miss him.
William Woodruff
Professor John Beckett writes:
In your obituary for William Woodruff (September 25) you write that "in 1946 he resumed teaching economic history at Oxford and in 1950 received a Houblon-Norman research fellowship... while at the same time studying for a BSc, MA and doctorate.
This is a conclusion from an author's note in Woodruff's book "Beyond Nab End", but it's not true.
From 1946 to 1953 he was a lecturer in economic history at the University of Nottingham and during this time he wrote a doctoral thesis on the British rubber industry under the supervision of Professor J.D. Chambers, which was later published in 1958 as "The British Rubber Industry".
He was born in 1951 in the United States on a Houblon-Norman scholarship, and spent the summer of 1952 at the universities of Illinois, Harvard and New York.
In 1953 he finally left Nottingham and went to Illinois.
It is not known why Woodruff wanted to cover up this part of his career.
