'car 'bee' that avoids collisions
To advance the development of accident prevention technologies, Nissan was inspired this time by nature, more precisely by bees.
The Japanese company has developed a robot whose flight is based on the swarm behaviour of bees and avoids accidents.
This robot is a biomimetic car robot drive or BR23C and represents the first step in the technologies for accident prevention.
The engineers from the Technical Development Center of Nissan Motor Co. developed this small robot in cooperation with the Research Center for Advanced Science and Technology of the renowned University of Tokyo (Japan).
According to Kazuhiro Doi, head of technology at PR and R & D, the BR23C is an extension of the four-layer Nissan safety shield.
This robot is designed to ensure that the cars of this brand are able to avoid collisions.
During the flight, each bee builds its own oval-shaped flight space, which is very similar to the Nissan safety shield.
But the most important are the bee ’ s compound eyes, which can be seen at an angle of 300 degrees in all directions, allowing it to fly undisturbed in its personal airspace without interruption.
In order to simulate the all-round perspective, the technicians developed the so-called Laser Range Finder (LRF).
He detects obstacles up to two meters away from the BR23C and within a radius of 180 degrees, calculates the distance to the object and sends a signal to a microprocessor onboard, which is immediately translated into a signal to avoid collision.
'The moment an obstacle is detected, the little robot will imitate the flight of the bees and will immediately change direction by turning its wheels by 90 ° or more to avoid the collision.
The main difference from any other system is that this evasive manoeuvre is absolutely instinctive.
If it were not so, the robot would not be able to react with sufficient speed to avoid obstacles, 'explains Toshiyuki Andoh, the director of the Laboratory of Mobility and the chief engineer of this project.
Unlike a bee, the robot can neither move up nor down, nor cross over; it can only move on two dimensions and in the direction that enables it to rotate its wheels and not in the infinite directions and in the infinite way that bees do.
For this reason, in addition to acceleration and deceleration functions, Nissan has used the rotation function to prevent the small robot from collisions.
'This device only needs a few seconds each to process the information and act according to this information.
It does not require to store neither the information nor the intuitive logic of the maneuvers, so it can work continuously with only a few dozen KB of memory.
This sounds surprising, but it ’ s not about the GBs, nor even the MBs of storage space.
This is the first step in the development of technologies for the immediate prevention of collisions, a technology that Nissan predicts to introduce in the production cars over the next ten years.
The robot works with lithium and polymer batteries that are lighter and last longer than a variety of lithium and ion batteries.
Another possible application of this technology in the future could be the integration of the unit with a GPS navigation system by satellite, to guide when driving to the destination, while avoiding the obstacles on the way.
