Morgan Stanley announced the entry of Mitsubishi UFJ Financial Group (MUFG) into its business, making it the first bank in Japan to spend $9 billion, acquiring 21% of its capital, an innovation stemming from a sharp fall in its stock price.
A week after a preliminary agreement was made public, the two banks announced that MUFG would buy 9.9% of Morgan Stanley ’ s common shares at a single price of $25.25, for a total of $3 billion.
The accepted price is below 19% of the share price of 31 August.
MUFG will invest an additional $6 billion in the purchase of convertible shares, which will secure a 10% profit and can be resold at a price of $31.25.
Morgan Stanley said that global business will be based on a single average price of $29, 28% above the current price.
Morgan Stanley ’ s stock, however, dropped by 6.79% to $23.07 against 17.00 GMT.
"This strategic link represents an important opportunity to accelerate Morgan Stanley's transition to holding bank status," said John Mack, CEO of the US group.
Morgan Stanley adopted this status last week, which should allow him to expand his business into new areas, but under the supervision of the Federal Reserve.
Their association with MUFG also confirms that the current financial crisis is forcing Wall Street ’ s biggest names to adopt a much more cautious stance than before.
The modalities presented on Monday also show that the agreement has changed over the last few days: last Monday Morgan simply stated that it would sell up to 20% of its shares to Japan for about $8.5 billion.
'A week ago, 'explained Toshihide Mizuno, Managing Director of MUFG in Tokyo,' we thought that the investment would consist entirely of ordinary shares.
But in view of the current economic and market situation, we wanted to reduce the risks and protect ourselves. '
Based on a balanced average price, MUFG will pay 7% below the price of Morgan Stanley shares.
And the deal will proceed with a reduction in earnings of about 20% per share.
The agreement provides that MUFG will be able to convert half of its preference shares into ordinary shares in a year if the latter are exchanged within a given period at more than 50% above the value of the sale, i.e. approximately $47.
Morgan Stanley assures that the funds provided by MUFG will enable it to capitalize on investment opportunities, strengthen its balance sheet and increase its sales.
A press spokesman for the group, however, refused to provide more detailed information on the strategic plans of the two new allies.
Following MUFG ’ s investment, Morgan Stanley should have a solvency ratio of about 15%, one of the best in the sector.
Morgan said he had 'significantly' reduced his balance sheet since the end of August.
The last few weeks have been tough for the group, which has seen its stock price fall by half as the price of insolvency insurance soared.
This price declined on Monday, but remained at a high level, at about 12%.
Goldman Sachs, the only 'survivor' of Wall Street's major investment banks following the bankruptcy of Bear Stearns and Lehman Brothers and the acquisition of Merrill Lynch, announced last week that it had raised $15 billion, in part from Berkshire Hathaway, Warren Buffett's group.
Rafael Correa this Monday in Quito.
Rebuild the republic around the socialism of the 21st century.
This is the common project of Venezuelan Hugo Chávez, Bolivian Evo Morales and Equatorial Rafael Correa.
It was the third person, following the example of his like-minded friends, who put the plan for a new constitution to the vote this Sunday.
Mission accomplished, because according to the public results, which amount to 80% of the votes, 64% voted 'yes' in the referendum.
According to these results, 28% voted 'no', 7% of the ballots were invalid and 0.7% were empty.
In order for the constitutional project to be adopted, more than half of the votes cast must be cast.
On Sunday, two polls conducted at the polling stations and a census by a non-governmental organisation announced a clear victory for the 'yes' vote, predicting between 63% and 70%.
In the night from Sunday to Monday Rafael Correa had demanded the victory of his constitutional project.
The 'Constitution has triumphed overwhelmingly', he said in Guayaquil, the seat of the government 280 kilometres southwest of Quito, and congratulated the Equatorial Guards.
Of course Rafael Correa was congratulated by Chávez and Morales, but also by his Chilean like-minded Michelle Bachelet.
The election, which was held in silence in accordance with the observation mission of the Organization of American States (OAS), referred to a text consisting of 444 points to safeguard the 'new socialism' advocated by the President.
The Constitutional project transfers state power to the economy by giving it the sole right to 'plan for development' in a country that lives largely from oil extraction by foreign companies and from the foreign currency that emigrants send into the country.
The project, promoted by the Correa elected in 2006, also confers greater power on the Head of State, who will be able to exercise up to two consecutive four-year mandates and will be able to dissolve the National Assembly.
Correa has already announced that he will make use of this power and seek a new mandate in February 2009.
The Constitution also safeguards the principle of free health care and education, which the President has already begun to introduce in this country of 13.9 million inhabitants, where 50% of the population live below the poverty line.
Finally, it also proposes to ban the presence of foreign troops, which will put an end to the agreement between Quito and Washington to use an equatorial base as a base for American anti-drug operations.
The 19 hostages were freed in Chad
An Egyptian command launched the attack on the kidnappers of the eleven tourists and their eight companions, who were captured ten days ago.
You are in Cairo.
The eleven European tourists and their eight Egyptian companions, who were held captive in the desert for eleven days, were brought back to the Egyptian capital this Monday afternoon safe and sound.
In the morning they were liberated by an Egyptian command in Chad.
Apparently in good condition, the hostages arrived on board a special plane at the military base Al Maza next to the international airport of Cairo around 3.30 pm.
They were taken directly, without being able to speak to the press, on board a helicopter to the hospital of Maadi, a quarter of foreigners in Cairo, to be examined there.
They all enjoy 'best health' and the kidnappers' were not paid a ransom ', Egyptian Tourism Minister Zoheir Garanna explained on the tarmac.
After being captured by a 4WD safari at the foot of Mount Ouanat in the border region of Egypt, Sudan and Libya on 19 September, the group of hostages was repeatedly transported from one hideout to the next by 35 unknown kidnappers.
It concerns eleven tourists - five Italians, five Germans and a Romanian woman - and besides eight Egyptians: two guides, four chauffeurs, a border guard and the director of the agency Aegyptus, organizer of the Safari.
An Egyptian security official said that 30 members of the special forces, aboard two helicopters, launched the attack at night, just before dawn.
'Shots were fired on both sides and half of the kidnappers were killed, the rest fled, 'said the person in charge, who wants to remain anonymous.
He said that a total of 150 members of the Egyptian special forces had been sent to Sudan, receiving support from German and Italian commandos.
The head of the Italian diplomats Franco Frattini reported from Belgrade, where he is, on the role played by secret agents and elements of the Italian special forces.
'We must acknowledge that we have achieved this result thanks to the professionalism and efficiency of our men from the intelligence and special forces, 'he explained without further detail.
He also denied that a ransom had been paid.
The previous day, the Sudanese army claimed to have stopped a patrol vehicle carrying the kidnappers, killing six of them, including the leader from Chad, and two arrests.
The army declared that it was in contact with a rebel group from Darfour, the Libération du Soudan ’ Unité (SLA ’ U) movement, which the movement immediately denied.
Letters - The Silent Majority of Culture
A debate on the financing of culture makes the headlines and is a central theme of the current election campaign.
So much the better.
But one area of our cultural life remains forgotten.
Who will stand up and denounce the wretched sums granted to small museums, archives, archaeological excavations or national historical sites that are dying of hunger?
Which politician will dare to remind the federal government that it neglects its monuments and its culturally significant buildings?
That in Quebec, as in Canada, there are no real laws that effectively protect our cultural heritage?
Did you know that the French Government is making EUR 3.5 million available solely for the restoration of Chinon Castle in the Loire Valley?
For our American neighbours, it is written in their country's constitution that the protection of cultural heritage is part of the American culture and that this cultural heritage must be protected by all citizens, all Members and all government districts, and by mutual agreement.
In Quebec, in the Association of Quebec Historical Societies, at least 40,000 volunteers, gathered in 211 historical societies, work intensively on history, save the numerous private archives with a few pennies, and preserve the archaeological remains.
They are also often the watchdogs of our cultural heritage, protesting with the strength of despair when patrons and decision-makers release their bulldozers onto our old stones and forgotten cemeteries.
When will there be a stage for history and cultural heritage?
Benelux, Governments Nationalize Sections of Fortis Bank
With a partial nationalisation, the Benelux countries want to help the Belgian Fortis Bank, which has been in turmoil due to the US financial crisis: The three states provide a total of EUR 11.2 billion to the bank and insurance institution, which also has branches in Hungary.
At the weekend, the governments of Belgium, Luxembourg and the Netherlands held high-level consultations with the President of the European Central Bank and the Competition Commissioner of the European Commission.
In the eurozone, Fortis is the first victim of the international financial market crisis that has been going on for a year, so decisions now taken in relation to the bank could set a precedent.
In line with the decision taken on Sunday night, all three countries are buying around 49 percent of the Bank ’ s shares.
The bank is expected to sell part of its holdings, most notably the insurance activities acquired by Dutch ABN Amro last year.
The shares of the Fortis last week started a steep decline, in the second half of the week already serious crisis scenarios appeared.
But analysts agree that the bank, with its 85,000 employees, is far too big to fail.
The institution ’ s securities fell by 12% on Friday to a 14-year low.
Since January, the value of the shares has fallen by more than two thirds.
In view of the current share prices, the market value of the Group amounts to EUR 14 billion, which is unrealistic according to management.
According to the management, the USD 700 billion US rescue package and the resulting uncertainty in the markets are to blame for the decline in Fortis shares.
On Monday, however, the courses increased slightly.
On Friday, Filip Dierckx was appointed as the Bank ’ s new Director General.
The financial institution was also on the search for a private buyer, but it found itself however no prospective customer with a material offer.
The Belgian government, however, sought reassurance - no investor should tremble for his money, it was said.
So far, there has been no panic among customers, and the bank ’ s branches have not been stormed.
In Hungary, Fortis has independent branches, but it also owns leasing companies.
Fox in the Chicken House
Because of a person ’ s drug use, life and health insurance companies in America often refuse to sign a contract with a customer.
Data protection experts fear that the data market may become uncontrollable.
"There are data protection programmes which link the use of medicinal product data in any case to the consent of the person concerned.
These should be in independent hands, otherwise we entrust the fox with the chickens "- quotes the Washington Post Richard Dick, developer of the program for the tracking of prescription data.
Insurance companies fix the fees and the payout amounts in case of damage depending on the health condition of the customer, and if the risk is estimated too high, the insurance is not taken out at all.
Previously, the customer was sent for a medical examination and the contract was concluded only with knowledge of the results of the examination.
Ten years ago, Dick invented a much more cost-effective method: he uses the customer ’ s identification number to obtain the data from pharmacies over the past year and a half, i.e. which products were purchased, and the program uses this to calculate what kind of illness the customer is suffering from and what his state of health is.
For example, if he regularly buys large quantities of cholesterol-lowering drugs, it could be concluded that his blood fat level is untreatably high, which would automatically put him in a higher risk group.
There are several versions of the program in circulation - some even define a risk multiplier, so that insurance companies only have to do the paperwork, but there are minor difficulties.
One of the disadvantages is that many drugs can be taken for different purposes, such as for migraine and hot flashes, but also for depression.
The latter is, from the perspective of insurers, a high-risk factor, while the previous ones did not.
For the consultation and processing of the data, own companies have been formed, which, before they refer the data, ask the patient for his consent.
In the meantime, they have to do this by law, although omissions have not yet been punished.
Some companies even process the results of laboratories and combine them with data on drug use to provide an even more accurate picture of patients ’ health status.
More and more companies have access to the data and it is becoming more difficult to control their use.
Although there is a separate data protection law for health data, its effect only extends to service providers in the health sector and insurance companies.
The bill has already been submitted to Congress, according to which the authorities could also control the data processing companies.
Dick Richard realizes that this is not enough, so he wants to develop his program further, so that the data can only be passed on with the consent of the person concerned.
Another question is, of course, that the person concerned can hardly prohibit access to his data, as the insurance companies would otherwise not conclude a contract with him.
And so the chickens are left to the mercy of the fox.
Global menu from Marseille
European Union and India double trade
Since the European Union and India are each other ’ s leading trade partners, this was the main topic at the ninth summit, among other global problems.
Today, the French-speaking Indian summit is also taking place, where cooperation in the nuclear energy sector is the main topic of discussion.
While the European Union recognizes that India is a rising democratic superpower that should be given more votes and voice in international affairs, member states have so far failed to agree on whether or not to support New Delhi ’ s permanent membership of the UN Security Council.
This issue was not even discussed at yesterday's ninth summit in Marseille.
The French President and current EU Council President Nicolas Sarkozy, Commission President José Manuel Barroso and Chief Diplomat Javier Solana received the Indian Prime Minister Manmohan Singh. An agreement was reached to double trade in the next five years, i.e. to a good 100 billion euros.
Given that trade rose from 25 billion to 55 billion between 2000 and 2007, this target is not at all ambitious.
With this in mind, the 26 existing civil flight agreements with India have been legally merged into one, so that air traffic will also be boosted in the future.
By 2009, India wants to sign the free trade agreement with the Union.
Sarkozy promised to speed up the pact.
The aim is to achieve a balance in the currently unbalanced relationship between the EU and India: while the Union is India ’ s number one partner, New Delhi ranks only ninth among the EU ’ s partners.
The summit was dedicated to global concerns.
These included the situation in Afghanistan and Pakistan, or terrorism, which both sides strongly condemned, and the convening of a UN conference.
The Doha Round should also be concluded, with both sides to blame for the failure.
The EU stressed its commitment to its energy and climate programme, which is to reduce pollutant emissions by at least 20% by 2020.
India also agreed with this, as well as with the proposal to conclude a kind of global compromise at the coming climate summit and to reduce greenhouse gas production by 50 percent by 2050.
The increase in food prices should also be combated, so both support the convening of an international conference on the financial crisis.
The Indian Prime Minister is visiting the French capital today, where he will hold a bilateral meeting to sign an agreement on the peaceful use of nuclear energy.
Meanwhile, Paris is hoping to win contracts worth EUR 20 billion from French companies for the construction of nuclear reactors in India.
According to agency reports, the agreement is to be concluded for 15 years.
Over 300 Italian publishers in Frankfurt
Strong presence of Italian publishers at the International Frankfurt Book Fair.
More than 300 Italian publishers will be present at the 60th Book Fair, the most important international event for the acquisition of rights.
The International Frankfurt Book Fair is expecting over 7,000 exhibitors from 101 countries for the current event. They will spread over the 171,790 square meters of the fair and introduce over 403,000 titles. Turkey will be the guest of honor of the event.
The Undersecretary for the Ministry of Cultural Heritage and Activities, Maria Giro, will represent the Italian Government in the exhibition hall during the opening ceremony: Italy will be represented in the 264 square meter exhibition space "Punto Italia".
This will be followed by a press conference near the room structure in Exhibition Hall 5.0 of the Book Fair: on this occasion, figures, trends and perspectives around the publishing industry in Italy will be discussed.
According to the data, the importance of books by foreign writers is declining in the entire adult and youth sector, in particular.
Billionaire Steve Fossett ’ s small plane disappeared a year ago
The small aircraft of Steve Fossett, the billionaire who disappeared on a flight over the Nevada desert on 3 September 2007, was found.
The parts were found on a high plateau of 3000 m height, in the area of the Sierra Nevada Mammoth Lakes between the states California and Nevada.
However, no human remains were found inside the aircraft.
The Sheriff of Madera County, John Anderson, fully rebutted the last doubts during a press conference: "The plane has been located, and a troop has been sent out. Now, we have the certainty that this is the plane with which Steve Fossett flew on the day of his disappearance."
Mr. Anderson also confirmed that no human remains were found on or near the plane.
The 63-year-old billionaire was declared dead in February.
The American Office of Traffic Safety (Ntsb) announced that a few hours after the sighting of the aircraft, a team was sent out to identify the aircraft: it is the Bellanca 8kcab, which was lost on 3 September 2007, after Fossett had taken off from Yerington in Nevada for a 3-hour flight.
Yesterday, also in California, not far from the Nevada border, some of Fossett ’ s personal belongings were finally found by a couple near their home on Mammoth Lakes.
These are two passports with the name of Fossett, both issued by the Federal Aviation Administration of illinois, cash and a jacket.
The search for Fossett had been abandoned a month after its disappearance.
The billionaire had conquered a place in history through a long run of records.
In 2002, in his sixth attempt, he was the first person to circle the globe in a hot-air balloon: a two-week, lonely flight.
Three years later, he flew around the world in a single non-stop flight.
Among his many records is also a high altitude flight of 15445 m over the Andes, this, however, with a co-pilot.
Glk, the ad you don't expect
